{"actor":{"id":"claude-opus-4-8","type":"agent"},"content":{"blocks":[{"text":"Done — `knownSecrets` is on globally now.\n\n## 2. Encryption (deferred design question) — my take: yes, but for a narrower reason than it first appears\n\nThe honest framing: encrypting this file **does not change the transport threat model at all**. The same secret already sits in plaintext right next to it — in the raw transcripts under `~/.claude/projects/…`, in your real `.env`, in shell history. The tool's whole trust boundary is *what gets shared*, and this file is never shared. So as pure \"protect the secret on my disk,\" encryption is close to theater.\n\n**But there's a real, distinct reason it's still worth doing:** this file is uniquely bad in one specific way — it *aggregates* your confirmed secrets into one predictably-named file with a schema literally labeled `\"values\"`. Scattered plaintext is one thing; a self-documenting `known-secrets.json` is a grep magnet — for a curious teammate with disk access, a backup/cloud-sync that scoops up the repo, an over-eager malware scanner, or just an accidental `cat`/screen-share. That aggregation risk is genuinely worse than the ambient plaintext, and it's the thing worth hardening.\n\nThe design constraint that shapes the answer: capture runs **silently on every turn** via a hook, so decryption has to be **non-interactive** — no passphrase prompt. That rules out anything where the key lives next to the file (pointless) or requires you to type something. The real version is:\n\n- **Cheap first step (almost free):** `chmod 0600` the file and dir so it's not group/world-readable. Doesn't stop aggregation-by-someone-who-is-you, but kills the casual multi-user case for nearly zero code.\n- **The real version:** encrypt at rest with a key in the **OS keychain** (macOS Keychain / libsecret / DPAPI). Then the file is opaque bytes at rest and only the `cledger` process with keychain access can read it — silent capture still works, casual reads and backup-scoops get nothing. Cost is the platform-specific keychain integration + key lifecycle + portability story (a teammate's machine has a different key, but that's fine — the store is per-machine local anyway).\n\nMy recommendation: park it as a roadmap item framed honestly as **\"defense against accidental read / aggregation, not against transport\"**, ship the `chmod 0600` as a trivial hardening whenever we next touch this file, and treat keychain encryption as the real-but-later work. I'll add that to the roadmap in Deliverable 3.\n\n## 3. The smoke test — one scope decision before I run it\n\nThe flow you described works exactly as you'd hope, and this repo is set up to demonstrate it for real. But there's a permanence wrinkle worth your call first, because it's an outward-facing push to your real GitHub project:\n\nThe demo is: inject a made-up secret (e.g. `smoke_test_password=NOTAREALSECRET_deadbeef1234`) into the ledger → `git push` → the pre-push scan catches it (capture tier misses `password=…`, scan tier's keyword rule flags it), holds back **only the ledger** while your code still pushes → `cledger redact --pattern` it → it lands in `known-secrets.json` → re-sync pushes the now-clean ledger. The raw fake value **never reaches origin** (the scan blocks it first).\n\nThe catch: the ledger is append-only. Even done cleanly, you'd permanently add a redacted event + a `redaction` companion event to the **real, shared** 1447-event ledger of this project. Harmless and secret-free, but not actually \"temporary.\"","type":"text"}],"role":"assistant"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","head":"33f522b9832b7de0b78d5f52e9cbb125d3f2403c","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:48648da3-5c2c-4827-96d5-7a6ed13224df","seq":355},"id":"ev1-54c1a98dc62165a9a6796fd3f6d2cb925abe0d4d61c2a22a7740ef588914c1de","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"202